com.github.mkrevuelta.JIntDatesConverter

Class DatesConverter

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.github.mkrevuelta.JIntDatesConverter.DatesConverter

  • public abstract class DatesConverter
extends Object
    This class translates calendar dates to and from Excel® dates —number of days since the start of year 1900 (*)— using plain-old, lightning-fast, integer arithmetics.

    It uses also a Pattern object and a few lookup tables which are initialized statically. They are never modified. Thus, the library is safe for multithread use.

    (*): Notes about Excel® dates:

    • 1900-01-00 is translated as 0. Though, it is considered invalid by DateOnly.isValid().
    • 1900-01-01 is day 1.
    • 1900-02-29, though not a real day, is considered valid for backward compatibility with Lotus123. It is translated as 60, Wednesday.
    • 1900-03-01 is day 61. It was a Thursday.
    • 9999-12-31 is day 2958465. This is the maximum date for Excel®. Though, this library considers valid and translates correctly all following dates up to...
    • 5881510-07-10, which is day Integer.MAX_VALUE. That is, 2147483647. A pretty nice Sunday, I hope, for whoever that walks the Earth by then.

    See the project page in GitHub

    Version:
    1
    Author:
    Martín Knoblauch Revuelta

    • Method Detail

      • getExcelDayFromDate

        public static int getExcelDayFromDate(DatesConverter.DateOnly date)
        This function translates a calendar date (year, month, day) from a DateOnly object to Excel® day number.

        This translation is slightly tolerant with some forms of invalid dates. The date 2020-02-31, for instance, is translated as 43892, which corresponds to 2020-03-02.

        Also, the special date 1900-01-00, though not strictly valid, is translated as day 0.

        Parameters:
        date - the DateOnly object to be translated
        Returns:
        the resulting Excel® day number if the input date is valid, -1 otherwise

      • getDateFromExcelDay

        public static DatesConverter.DateOnly getDateFromExcelDay(int excelDay)
        Translates from an Excel day number to a calendar date (year, month, day) in the form of a DateOnly object.

        The Excel® day 0 is translated as 1900-01-00, which is not strictly valid.

        Negative day numbers are also translated as 1900-01-00.

        Parameters:
        excelDay - Excel® day number
        Returns:
        corresponding calendar date as a DateOnly object if the input is greater than 0, the default DateOnly (1900-01-00) otherwise

      • getExcelDayFromString_YYYY_dash_MM_dash_DD

        public static Integer getExcelDayFromString_YYYY_dash_MM_dash_DD(String date,
                                                                 Integer defaultValue)
        This function is a convenience wrapper for getExcelDayFromDate(). It works with dates in strings with the format yyyy-MM-dd instead of DateOnly objects. In addition, the caller can specify the default value to be returned when the parsing fails or the date is invalid.
        Parameters:
        date - date string in yyyy-MM-dd format
        defaultValue - special value to be returned if the parsing fails or the date is invalid
        Returns:
        the resulting Excel® day number if the input is a valid date, defaultValue otherwise
        See Also:
        getExcelDayFromDate(com.github.mkrevuelta.JIntDatesConverter.DatesConverter.DateOnly)

        public static String getString_YYYY_dash_MM_dash_DD_FromExcelDay(Integer excelDay)
        This function is a convenience wrapper for getDateFromExcelDay(). It returns dates in strings with the format yyyy-MM-dd instead of DateOnly objects.
        Parameters:
        excelDay - Excel® day number
        Returns:
        corresponding calendar date string in yyyy-MM-dd format if the input is greater than 0, "1900-01-00" otherwise.
